    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1878-06-05T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1878-06-05T00:00:00-05:00" n="520" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d520">
                <head>No. 515.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Maynard</persName> to Mr. <persName type="to">Evarts</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Legation of the United States</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Constantinople</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1878-06-05">
                            <hi rend="italic">June</hi> 5, 1878</date>.
                                (Received July 3.)</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 255.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to announce still another
                            change in the high office of Grand Vizier.</p>
                <p>Last night the imperial hatt was published at the Porte, proclaiming <pb facs="0948" n="886" xml:id="pg_886"/> His Highness Safvet Pasha, now
                            and for a long time past minister of foreign affairs, Grand Vizier, in
                            place of His Highness Mehemet Buchdi Pasha who had held the office just
                            one week.</p>
                <p>Phosphor Mustapha Pasha is appointed minister of war in place of His
                            Highness Mahmond Dam ad Pasha, who received the office ten days ago.</p>
                <p>There is apparently little significance to be attached to these changes
                            beyond the distracted condition of the Ottoman Government.</p>
                <p>The caution and prudence of the new Grand Vizier will be more likely to
                            prevent mischief than to suggest remedies.</p>
                <p>I am, &amp; c.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>HORACE MAYNARD.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
